post_text: The North Powder School District has moved the start date with students to September 8, 2020. This change was made due to a district determination that it would be in the best interest of families, students, and staff to delay the first day of school with students. In order to prepare for Comprehensive Distance Education per current ODE guidelines, there is additional professional development and planning that will need to occur for staff, students and families. This professional development will include online curriculum training, implementation of the district's operational blueprint for onsite education, and opportunities to meet with students and parents to update them on the online process and answer questions. This change in the starting date will not change any other dates on the calendar at the current time due to ODE guidelines allowing additional hours for professional development to count towards instructional time.

From the Oregon Department of Education:

As we prepare for school in the fall, health and safety concerns are at the forefront of everyone’s mind. Oregon Healthy Schools, a collaboration between the Oregon Department of Education and the Oregon Health Authority, is planning to create a series of short videos to address practical tips on how to stay safe and healthy. Your help is needed to prioritize topic areas.

Please complete the Oregon Healthy Schools Video Development Survey which should take no more than three minutes of your time. The survey will provide valuable information as we move forward with this project. This is a quick turn-around and the survey will close Tuesday, July 21st, at 5:00 pm.

Thank you for your participation!

post_text: We will have high school registration next Monday, July 20th starting with incoming seniors at 4:00 p.m. Juniors will come at 4:45, followed by sophomores at 5:30, and incoming freshmen at 6:15 p.m. We will have to follow the guidelines for schools with no more than 10 in a group, but we have administration and counselors available to spread out in different classrooms. We will have the course catalog available by the end of the week, as well as the schedules so students can take a look. Middle school students will be sent a survey next week to register for their top elective choices. We will send that to their school email and will notify parents when that is available. If you have any questions, please email us.

post_text: State FFA Degree Spotlight - Zachary Sandberg: Zachary’s primary SAE over the course of his FFA experience has centered around a Swine breeding operation. Zach has been creative in improving his bottom line by acquiring feed from non traditional sources and has been successful in marketing by utilizing social media outlets. Last year Zachary was the Eastern Oregon District Swine Production Proficiency Winner, and was a finalist at the state level. Zachary has competed in Ag Sales, Parliamentary Procedure, Tractor Driving, leadership ceremony contest, Crops, Soils, and Livestock Judging. Zachary has also taken sheep market projects to the Eastern Oregon Livestock Show. Zachary’s favorite FFA event is traveling to State Convention and he highly recommends young members to participate in that event.

Hunter’s favorite community service activity was delivering wreaths to the elderly at Christmas time.

Attention North Powder Agriculture Students:

Tomorrow Tuesday May 12th all North Powder Agriculture Students should be receiving a google form with instructions on voting for the 2020-2021 North Powder FFA officer team.

The google voting form will come through each student's google classroom. If students are still in need of help accessing their google classroom please email or call Mr. Bingham.

Students will have until Friday May 15th to vote. Votes will be tallied over the weekend, followed by a virtual meeting of the new officer team. After the meeting the new officer team will be announced through social media. Most likely Tuesday of next week.

The students who have submitted their names as potential officer candidates are: Eric Newman, Ariel Pointer, Trinity Nesser, Kenzie Leggett, Mady Leggett, Dallee Bingham, Zachary Sandberg, and Cooper Secl.

post_text:
This week is teacher appreciation week and our teacher spotlight is Laura Bates. She has been teaching for 31 years. Her favorite thing about teaching is building positive relationships with students, staff and families, and the joy that comes to her from being around and teaching students. There have been many hilarious comments that young elementary students have made around Mrs. Bates. They speak what’s on their mind with all honesty! During quarantine, her youngest son, husband and Mrs. Bates have delivered cards and flowers to all of their neighbors, which brought many smiles to their faces! When shelter in place is over, she is very much looking forward to getting to see and spend time with all of her family.
She greatly misses seeing all of the students and staff, and she hopes everyone is staying healthy, safe, and enjoying time with their family at home.

post_text: This week is Teacher Appreciation week, and we sure do appreciate ours! Our teacher spotlight is Tristan Patton. He has been teaching for 7 years. His favorite thing about teaching is working with people of all ages. The funniest thing that has ever happened to him while teaching is joking with students and the small pranks. During quarantine, he and his family have built a small Greenhouse with found materials. One thing he is looking forward to when shelter in place is over is planning for an event( Marathon/concert/dinner party/vacation), and getting to do that activity. He is really looking forward to being able to see everyone regularly again, and hopefully knowing himself a little bit better, too.

post_text:
This week is Teacher Appreciation week, and we sure do appreciate ours! Our teacher spotlight is Stephanie Mays. She has been teaching for 19 years and her favorite thing about teaching is
when the students “click” with a new concept being taught! The “aha” moment is amazing! The funniest thing that has ever happened to her while teaching is when a preschool student once came up to her and told her she was a pig in another life. She asked how she knew and she said because she loved “shlop!” She told her when the farmer brought it to her she got excited! She still loved it to that day! (She was 4!) During quarantine, she has been remodeling their kitchen and when shelter in place is over, she is looking forward to the hugs, smiles and high fives from her students! It makes her so happy!

post_text: This week is Teacher Appreciation week, and we sure do appreciate ours! Our teacher spotlight is Dana Marlia. She has been teaching for 18 years and her favorite thing about teaching is the students' various senses of humor. She said there are multiple funniest things that have happened to her while teaching. During the quarantine, she has been working on a lot of house projects—before summer, ahead of schedule. When the shelter in place is over, she is looking forward to teaching in person! She also is looking forward to walking whatever direction she wants in Albertsons, hugging random strangers, Church, going to Costco and Target. As you can tell, there are multiple things she is looking forward to.

post_text: This week is Teacher Appreciation week, and we sure do appreciate ours! Our teacher spotlight is Geneva Olson. She has been teaching for 8 years. Her favorite thing about teaching is the reward of making a difference in children's lives every day. She finds joy in kids being brave and learning new things with their peers. She reminds us that no two days are the same and kids come to school ready to learn something new! It makes her smile when a student says "it's time to go home already, I was having fun!" The funniest thing that has ever happened to her while teaching was the year she taught middle school science and her eighth grade students decided to take the masking tape off of her desk. One table group thought it would be clever to wrap the tape around themselves in a circle. It was hilarious when the bell rang and they were literally stuck together! She is looking forward to connecting with people and doing aerial yoga when the shelter in place is over.

post_text:
This week is Teacher Appreciation week, and we sure do appreciate ours! Our teacher spotlight is Brad Dunten. Mr. Dunten has been teaching for 10 years. His favorite thing about teaching is seeing growth with students and their enjoyment to live a physically fit life.
The funniest thing that has ever happened to him while teaching he says is the daily responses by elementary students. The one thing he is looking forward to when things get back to normal is getting back to physical education with his students. He says he truly enjoys watching their growth daily and how they push themselves to the limits.

post_text: This week is Teacher Appreciation week, and we sure do appreciate ours! Our teacher spotlight is Casey Townsend. She has been teaching for 6 years at North Powder. Her favorite thing about teaching is building relationships with the students, advocating for students who cannot advocate for themselves and the amazing friendships with her co workers. The funniest thing that has ever happened to her while teaching is when she waxed Mr. Dixon’s nose and ear hairs for Badger News! During quarantine, Titus has helped her renovate their backyard shed into a “Zen Den” for Mrs. T ..... so she can escape her own kids! Ha ha. When the shelter in place is over, she is looking forward to going on a trip to the coast and to no longer feel guilty when she goes into a store. She said if she were not a teacher, she would love to have her own little coffee shop and sell baked goods and coffee!

post_text:
This week is Teacher Appreciation week, and we sure do appreciate ours! Our teacher spotlight is Jessie Street. She has been teaching for 10 years. Her favorite thing about teaching is creating opportunities for students to be proud of themselves. She loves how a student’s face lights up when they love something they’ve created. The funniest thing that has ever happened to her while teaching is probably when Brandon Zink took a photo of her, editing it with goofy Snapchat filters and taping it to her door.
During quarantine, Mrs. Street has played movie theatre with her kindergartner. They set up a big screen and projector and a cash register. She punched tickets and did concessions and everything 🥰 When the shelter in place is over, Mrs. Street is looking forward to hugs! And spontaneous, regular interaction with friends and students. She LOVES her dog, Ziggy. She's not sure how she would get through these days without him and their daily exercise!

post_text: This week is Teacher Appreciation week, and we sure do appreciate ours! Our teacher spotlight is Allie Scott. She has been teaching for 12 years. Her favorite thing about teaching is sharing herlove for learning with her students. She also loves working with so many different age groups, each grade level has something special about it. The funniest thing that has ever happened to her while teaching is during the years she taught first grade there were many funny conversations that came up. Topics such as: what to feed Santa’s reindeer, how to hold in a fart, and things they’ve heard their parents say at home, we’re some memorable ones. First graders have such curiosity and know how to make people laugh; there was never a dull moment. Mrs. Scott is looking forward to spending time with family and friends once the shelter in place is over. Thank you Mrs. Scott!

post_text: DARE graduation occurred in a different way than normal last Thursday during a 5th grade Zoom meeting. Deputy Humphries joined Ms. Culley so they could listen to the students do an outstanding job sharing their DARE essays. The great surprise was Deputy Humphries and Ms. Culley delivered the students their DARE t-shirts with a sweet treat. We are proud of their efforts and sure appreciate the work of Deputy Humphries! He's the best SRO and DARE teacher in Oregon!

post_text: This week is Teacher Appreciation week, and we sure do appreciate ours! Our teacher spotlight is Nic Maszk. He has been teaching for two years and his favorite thing about teaching is finding ways to make learning enjoyable for students. The funniest thing that has happened to him while teaching is when a student dressed up as him and taught the first two minutes of class perfectly. During COVID-19, he has had more time to run and working on big house projects. When the shelter in place is over, he is looking forward to getting to run in races. He also wishes you all are doing well.

We wish you the best of luck!

Please pay by check if at all possible as there will not be change available. post_text:
NPCS Senior Spotlight is Estefania Balderas Ochoa.
Estefania loves volleyball and dance. After graduation, she plans
on working during the summer and then move to La Grande. She plans on attending Eastern Oregon University in pursuit of a a nursing degree. A funny fact about Estefania is she usually jumps up and down when school is closed for a day but now that school is cancelled, she really wants to go back to school. We totally understand that. Estefania says she really misses all of her teachers and classmates. Her hope is that once everything gets better, the seniors can get closure before they all head off to spread their wings and grow on their own. She wants everyone to stay safe and healthy! We are proud of you Estefania and know that your wings will make you soar! Best of luck!

post_text: Our Senior Spotlight is Brenden Richard Golar. Brenden really loves playing baseball! He has played from little league all the way up to high school. He enjoyed every second of it. After graduation, Brenden plans on attending BMCC to pursue his dream in diesel mechanics. His mom shared that funny moments about Brenden is when he was always with his father. Almost every time they were together they would always be laughing together. They would make everything seem funny and it was always hard to not crack a smile or laugh with them together. There sarcastic humor would always lighten up the room when they were together! Brenden is such an amazingly kind hearted person. He is always there to help anyone that needs it. His infectious smile and amazing laugh can always lighten up anyone's day. We are proud of his accomplishments and look forward to seeing where life takes him. His father would be proud of him! We know these things about Brenden and are proud of him. We can't wait to see where life takes him. Best of luck Bren!

Our NPCS Senior Spotlight is Monica Barajas. Monica loves playing her trumpet, creating music pieces with her sisters, and performing with them. She has been involved in honor band and soccer during her time at Powder Valley. After graduation, Monica plans on getting a job close to home. She wants to stay close to her family
A funny fact about Monica is that when she was 2, her mom caught her climbing off the dinner table. Her mom asked her if she was eating the chocolates that were up there and with her little face covered in chocolate ...she said no. Monica puts a smile on our faces and we know she is going to be great. Her family is so proud of her too. They say she is an amazing daughter and an amazing big sister to her baby brother and the rest of her siblings and has proven to be a responsible young adult. We love you! Best of luck Monica!

post_text: NPCS Senior Spotlight for this evening is Roper Jacob Bingham. Roper is a guy who loves hunting. He has been involved in football, basketball, track, FFA, Honor's Society, and is currently our ASB President. After graduation, Roper plans on attending Utah State and pursuing a degree in Agribusiness: Farm & Ranch. Best of luck Roper. We know you will do great things!

post_text: NPCS Senior Spotlight is Dominick Dale Warren Grende. Dominick loves shed hunting in his free time. He has been involved in football, basketball, and track at school, but also enjoys hunting. After graduation, Dominick plans on getting a job. The funny thing about Dominick, according to his family, is he doesn't always pay attention!! One time while going to a wrestling tournament he walked face first into a pole. Dominick is a great kid who loves the outdoors! He loves to hunt, Fish, hunt for deer and elk sheds and pretty much anything else outdoors. He loves all sports, but his family believes his favorite is track! He's super bummed to not be able to compete his senior year!! We hear you Dominick. We are proud of you and glad to be a part of your education. Best of luck!

post_text: Our NPCS Senior Spotlight is Anna Lynell Brocato. She is a member of the class of 2020. She loves horses, dogs, and snakes and loves singing as loud as possible. She has been active in acting, singing, art, track, working at the ranch, and horsing around. After graduation, Anna plans to attend a community college or job training. She wants to join a choir and train her horse. She has an eclectic taste in music, video games, and humor and claims she can hack any device. Her laugh is boisterous. She believes that life can be hectic, but put your head down and charge through it. We have enjoyed having Anna at NPCS.

post_text:
Join Us Every Weekday Morning!

We must admit; we are pretty cooped up on our end. New routines, working from home, kiddos at home, NO SPORTS?! We know… This is going to be tough. However, as you can probably tell from the image above, the Trail Blazers are always cooking up new ways to be a part of your family.

PE with the Trailblazers! This is on Instagram. Check out the information below.

This week, we launched our Virtual PE Program, presented by Moda Health. Every weekday morning at 10:00 A.M. PST, our @BlazerCommunity Instagram goes live with a session led by a health & wellness instructor in our network. The 30-minute long sessions encourage your child to use their imagination, get active and practice mindfulness!

Virtual PE is intended for children K-5, but we encourage your whole family to join the fun. Be sure to follow us on Instagram and turn on notifications, so you don’t miss a thing!

During this difficult time, we do have some good news to share. Our counselor, Luke Matteucci is available to your child. Luke has been working at our school on Wednesdays, so some of our students are already familiar with him. He is available over the phone and/or video conferencing. You can reach him on his work cell at 541.910.8841. He is available most Tuesdays mornings and Wednesday all day. Please leave him a message and he will get back to you.

If your child would like to visit with Marji Lind, you may e-mail her at marji.lind@npowdersd.org or call her at 208.918.0387.

post_text:
COVID-19 Information
What if I decide to keep my child home from school even if it’s not closed?
Work with your child’s teachers and principal at your local school district. They can talk to you about their attendance policies and can explain any procedures they have to support education from home.

At this time, the Oregon Health Authority and Oregon Department of Education recommend against closing schools and campuses where no cases of COVID-19 are present.
text:
COVID-19 Information
What if I decide to keep my child home from school even if it’s not closed?
Work with your child’s teachers and principal at your local school district. They can talk to you about their attendance policies and can explain any procedures they have to support education from home.

At this time, the Oregon Health Authority and Oregon Department of Education recommend against closing schools and campuses where no cases of COVID-19 are present.

post_text:
COVID-19 Information
Should my child stay home?
The main symptoms of COVID-19 are cough, fever and shortness of breath. If your child merely has a runny nose, your child may attend school.

Many school district policies state that a child should be fever free for 24 hours before they return to school. If your child has cough, fever and shortness of breath and you are concerned about possible COVID-19, call your local health department or health care provider. They will help you decide if you need an appointment. If so, they can help you plan a way to enter a clinic in a way that avoids potentially infecting others.

shared_text:
Baker County Oregon Health Department
February 13 at 12:09 PM ·

Immunizations will be available for students affected by school exclusion on a walk-in basis on February 14th from 8:30-11:30 am and 1:30-4:00 pm at Baker County Health Department. A parent or guardian must accompany the child.

Please bring:

*Your child’s exclusion letter
*Immunization records
*Insurance card for billing (we also need the policy holder’s social security number and date of birth).

For more information on school exclusion read below.

February 19th is school exclusion day. If your child’s immunizations are incomplete or if their immunization record has not been provided to the school your child attends your child will not be able to attend school starting February 19th until they are complete or the school has the proper documentation. It is the parents responsibility to provide documentation to the school.

Our next walk-in for school exclusion will be February 19th.

Nominations for the 2020 Crystal Apple "Excellence in Education" Awards are now open. These annual awards recognize outstanding educators and school staff in eastern Oregon school districts.

Those eligible to be nominated are full-time or part-time employees who have worked in the district for one year. Crystal Apple Awards can be given to principals, assistant principals, teachers, paraeducators, office staff, maintenance staff and other district staff. They can be nominated by administrators, teachers, paraeducators, school staff, students, parents or community members.

Deadline for nominations is April 1, 2020.
Nomination Form: https://imesd.k12.or.us/crystal-apple-award-nomination-form
Information Page: https://imesd.k12.or.us/crystalapple/home

January is School Board Recognition Month. The Oregon School Boards Association honors the unpaid elected volunteers who serve on Oregon’s 197 local school boards, 19 ESD boards and 17 community college boards.

The North Powder School District thanks our board members for their dedicated service to North Powder students and to public education in our state!

post_text:
Oregon school districts are currently in the process of preparing their applications for the Student Investment Account (SIA), which is new grant money for the state's school districts. In the past couple of months, North Powder School District has asked for input from students, staff, parents and the community to gather information to develop priorities. In the spring, we will be sharing our plan with you.

In the meantime, for more information, please refer to the SIA Flyer: https://npowder.k12.or.us/sites/npowder.k12.or.us/files/inline-files/SIA%20Only%20Flyer.pdf

or visit ODE's Student Success Act page: https://www.oregon.gov/ode/StudentSuccess/Pages/default.aspx

Oregon Regional Teacher of the Year nominations end in just over two weeks! If you know a great North Powder teacher, nominate them now at: https://oregonteacheroftheyear.org/nominate/

The Oregon Department of Education, in partnership with the Oregon Lottery, sponsors this award to honor exemplary educators in every region of the state!

• Nominations are open statewide through January 31, 2020.
• InterMountain ESD will select a winner from our region.
• Regional Teachers of the Year will be honored across the state in May 2020!

Regional Teachers of the Year will receive a cash prize of $500.

Anyone can nominate a teacher! All Oregonians are encouraged to nominate their favorite teacher today.

Do you know a great teacher? The Oregon Department of Education, in partnership with the Oregon Lottery, is pleased to announce the continuation of Oregon Regional Teacher of the Year to honor exemplary educators in every region of the state!

Anyone can nominate a teacher! All Oregonians are encouraged to nominate their favorite teacher today at: https://oregonteacheroftheyear.org/nominate/

• Nominations are open statewide through January 31, 2020.
• Oregon Education Service Districts will select a winner from their region.
• Regional Teachers of the Year will be honored across the state in May 2020!
Regional Teachers of the Year will receive a cash prize of $500 and will be celebrated across the state.
